definition.value: The binding activity of a molecule that brings together an anion exchanger and one or more other molecules, permitting them to function in a coordinated way.
Catalysis of the cleavage of a 5' flap structure in DNA, but not other DNA structures -  processes the 5' ends of Okazaki fragments in lagging strand DNA synthesis.
An enzyme complex that catalyzes the ligation of glutamate to cysteine, forming glutamylcysteine.
Catalysis of the reaction -  a nucleoside diphosphate + H2O -eq- a nucleotide + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  a nucleoside triphosphate + H2O -eq- nucleoside diphosphate + phosphate.

Stimulates the exchange of guanyl nucleotides associated with a GTPase of the Rab family. Under normal cellular physiological conditions, the concentration of GTP is higher than that of GDP, favoring the replacement of GDP by GTP in association with the GTPase.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5,6-dihydrouracil + NADP+ -eq- uracil + NADPH + H+.

label.value: single-stranded DNA-dependent ATP-dependent DNA helicase activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate, in the presence of single-stranded DNA -  drives the unwinding of a DNA helix.

label.value: single-stranded DNA-dependent ATP-dependent DNA helicase complex

definition.value: A protein complex that possesses single-stranded DNA-dependent DNA helicase activity.
Catalysis of the transfer of the lipoyl group from lipoyl-AMP to the lysine residue of lipoate-dependent enzyme.

A complex of proteins that, in vitro, stimulates intra-Golgi transport -  a 13S complex, about 800 kDa in size and consists of at least five polypeptides. In yeast, this complex is called the Sec34|35 complex and is composed of eight subunits (Sec34p, Sec35p, Dor1p, Cod1p, Cod2p, Cod3p, Cod4p, and Cod5p).

Heterotrimeric enzyme complex, which in humans is composed of two large subunits of the same size, and one smaller subunit. Functions in the addition of nucleotide-activated sugars onto the polypeptide.
Increases the rate of GTP hydrolysis by a GTPase of the Ral family.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a SH3 domain (Src homology 3) of a protein, small protein modules containing approximately 50 amino acid residues found in a great variety of intracellular or membrane-associated proteins.
Catalysis of the insertion of a dCMP residue opposite a template abasic site in DNA.

Enables the directed movement of cholesterol into, out of or within a cell, or between cells. Cholesterol is the principal sterol of vertebrates and the precursor of many steroids, including bile acids and steroid hormones.
Catalysis of the movement of phospholipids from one membrane bilayer leaflet to the other, by an ATP-independent mechanism.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any triester of glycerol.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a sequence of cytosine residues in an RNA molecule.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with U-rich sequence in the 3'-end of nuclear-transcribed mRNAs -  required for cytoplasmic polyadenylylation.

label.value: cyclic nucleotide-dependent guanyl-nucleotide exchange factor activity

definition.value: Stimulates the exchange of guanyl nucleotides associated with a GTPase -  dependent on the presence of a cyclic nucleotide.

A protein complex located in the mitochondrion. It contains flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD) that, together with an acyl-CoA dehydrogenase, forms a system that oxidizes an acyl-CoA molecule and reduces ubiquinone and other acceptors in the mitochondrial electron transport system.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a fibroblast growth factor.

Catalysis of the reaction -  histone N6-acetyl-L-lysine + H2O -eq- histone L-lysine + acetate. This reaction requires the presence of NAD, and represents the removal of an acetyl group from a histone.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with Rab protein, any member of the Rab subfamily of the Ras superfamily of monomeric GTPases.

An assembly of four or five subunits which form a structure with an extracellular N-terminus and a large loop that together form the ligand binding domain. The C-terminus is intracellular. The ionotropic glutamate receptor complex itself acts as a ligand gated ion channel -  on binding glutamate, charged ions pass through a channel in the center of the receptor complex. NMDA receptors are composed of assemblies of NR1 subunits (Figure 3) and NR2 subunits, which can be one of four separate gene products (NR2A-D). Expression of both subunits are required to form functional channels. The glutamate binding domain is formed at the junction of NR1 and NR2 subunits. NMDA receptors are permeable to calcium ions as well as being permeable to other ions. Thus NMDA receptor activation leads to a calcium influx into the post-synaptic cells, a signal thought to be crucial for the induction of NMDA-receptor dependent LTP and LTD.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with Wnt-protein, a secreted growth factor involved in signaling.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  tRNA-uracil + acceptor -eq- tRNA-dihydrouridine + reduced acceptor.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the enzyme DEAD|H-box RNA helicase.
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  dicarboxylate(out) + Na+(out) -eq- dicarboxylate(in) + Na+(in).
Combining with a semaphorin, and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (R)-pantetheine + H(2)O -eq- (R)-pantothenate + cysteamine.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with Ral protein, any member of the Ral subfamily of the Ras superfamily of monomeric GTPases.
Catalysis of the reaction -  D-myo-inositol 1,3,4-trisphosphate + H2O -eq- myo-inositol 1,3-bisphosphate + phosphate.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an aryl hydrocarbon receptor.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with vinculin, a protein found in muscle, fibroblasts, and epithelial cells that binds actin and appears to mediate attachment of actin filaments to integral proteins of the plasma membrane.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5-oxo-L-proline + ATP + 2 H(2)O -eq- L-glutamate + ADP + 2 H(+) + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  CDP + alcohol -eq- CMP + phosphatidyl alcohol.

Catalysis of the hydrolysis of a substrate by a catalytic mechanism that involves a catalytic triad consisting of a serine nucleophile that is activated by a proton relay involving an acidic residue (e.g. aspartate or glutamate) and a basic residue (usually histidine).
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-cysteine + O(2) -eq- 3-sulfino-L-alanine + H(+).
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + glycine -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + sarcosine.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine + phosphatidylinositol -eq- UDP + N-acetyl-D-glucosaminylphosphatidylinositol.
A heterodimeric complex that catalyzes the trimming of glucose residues from N-linked core glycans on newly synthesized glycoproteins.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + diphthine + NH(4)(+) -eq- ADP + diphthamide + H(+) + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-aspartate + acetyl-CoA -eq- N-acetyl-L-aspartate + CoA + H(+).
Catalysis of the reaction -  palmitoyl-CoA + glycoprotein -eq- CoA + N-palmitoylglycoprotein.

Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + histone L-lysine -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + histone N6-methyl-L-lysine. The methylation of peptidyl-lysine in histones forms N6-methyl-L-lysine, N6,N6-dimethyl-L-lysine and N6,N6,N6-trimethyl-L-lysine derivatives.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + calmodulin L-lysine -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + calmodulin N6-methyl-L-lysine.
Catalysis of the transfer of a myristoyl group to the N6 nitrogen atom on a lysine residue of a peptide or protein molecule.
